<subsection xml:id="beamer2-summary">
<title>Student Perspective</title>

<p>
During class, I encountered problems with watching my curly bracket swhen
build newcommands.  The more complex a new command becomes, the more
important it is to watch your curly brackets.  When learning about
newcommands, I thought they were similar to when building a functionâ€™s
definition with a parameter in other programming language like Python. 
Both allow you to pass arguments through them and reduce complexity in
code.
</p>

<p>
<c>\newcommand</c> is a way to prevent long and similar code from repeating
in your <latex/> file.  <c>\newcommand</c> is composed of three main
parts
<c>\newcommand{command call name}{# of arguments}{command syntax}</c>
Note: You can have more than one
function to pass your argument(s) through. When you call a new command it
will be: the <c>\call_name{argument 1}...{arguments n}</c> where <c>n</c> is your total amount of arguments. The major
takeaway from introducing <c>\newcommand</c> is that it allows your <latex/> code to be concise,
easier to read, and faster to write.</p>
</subsection>

