<section xml:id="bibtex-environments"><!--09/28-->
<title>BibTeX</title>

<subsection xml:id="bibtex-preview">
<title>Preview</title>
<p> We will introduce the powerful BibTeX referencing system.</p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="bibtex-review">
<title>Review</title>
<p><url href="https://seanteachesmath.github.io/books/tech-prof-math-stat/notes/day12.pdf">Day 12 Notes (pdf)</url>.
</p>

<p>BibTeX a a tremendously powerful and useful bibliography processing
system.  It also has auxiliary programs (e.g., BibDesk) that are very
useful for reference/bibliography management.  With no special commands we can use
the <c>\cite{citekey}</c> command to reference a item by its citekey. 
The citekey is the code associated with the bibliographic information given
in the <c>.bib</c> file.  The file is specified by the command
<c>\bibliography{filename.bib}</c> and the style is given by the command
<c>\bibliographystyle{name}</c>.  Reasonable choices for bibliography
styles are 
<ol>
<li><p><c>plain</c> - reference list sorted alphabetically, in-text reference refers to numerical order</p></li>
<li><p><c>unsrt</c> - reference list sorted in order of in-text referencing</p></li>
<li><p><c>alpha</c> - reference list sorted alphabetically, in-text reference refers to unique, abbreviated author-year code</p></li>
</ol>
</p>

<figure xml:id="bibtex-flow">
<image source="./images/bibtexreed.png" width="80%">
</image>
<caption>A nice 
<a href="https://www.reed.edu/cis/help/LaTeX/BibtexOverview.html">diagram</a>
illustrating the interplay between <latex/> and BibTeX. My only
complaint about the illustration is the naming of the file <c>
foo.bib</c>, in general this .bib file can have its own unique name.
Notice that <c>foo.aux</c>, <c>foo.bbl</c> derive their names from the
original <c>.tex</c> file. Once you have run BibTeX, look at the
corresponding <c>.bbl</c> file. In fact, it is readable just as your
<c>.tex</c> file.</caption>
</figure>

<p>Look here for <a
href="http://mirrors.ibiblio.org/CTAN/macros/latex/contrib/natbib/natnotes.pdf"> 
a tremendous reference sheet on natbib</a>.  Using the <c>natbib</c> package opens 
up a variety of new citation formats beyond simple parenthetical citations.
</p>
</subsection>

